      <body>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112528400">
            <form>
               <orth>torr dubh</orth>
            </form>
            <def>seaweed gathered at end of year and stacked on machair land left to rot and used as fertiliser for potatoes in spring.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112448408">
            <form>
               <orth>leathag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>ruffled bit of seaweed attached to tangles. Same as ‘liathag’.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112515872">
            <form>
               <orth>“gille piullagach is loth pheallagach”</orth>
            </form>
            <def>if these two characters present in a household, taken as a sign of impending future prosperity. Both could be trained for gainful employment.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112531856">
            <form>
               <orth>biorach</orth>
            </form>
            <def>dogfish.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112479224">
            <form>
               <orth>reubainn</orth>
            </form>
            <def>a beard.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112552736">
            <form>
               <orth>sgal</orth>
            </form>
            <def>a period of time. “Bha e sgal mhór am Beinn a Bhaoghla.”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112437752">
            <form>
               <orth>ionnlad</orth>
            </form>
            <def>to clean, wash yourself. “Tha mi dol gam ionnlad fhéin.” Common in Wester Ross.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112536176">
            <form>
               <orth>blaighteachas</orth>
            </form>
            <def>a little or part. “Tha blaighteachas tiorramachaidh orra an diugh.”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112505504">
            <form>
               <orth>oil eas</orth>
               <pron>[sic]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[sic] fuss, stir. “Ach an oil eas a bha thall an sud an diugh.” Not sure whether or not this is one word.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112427888">
            <form>
               <orth>geadadh</orth>
            </form>
            <def>to beat.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112452080">
            <form>
               <orth>baltag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>said of someone with chubby facial features.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112512344">
            <form>
               <orth>steòrnadh</orth>
            </form>
            <def>to wave.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112462520">
            <form>
               <orth>farchlais</orth>
            </form>
            <def>eavesdropping.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112462448">
            <form>
               <orth>spìdeal</orth>
            </form>
            <def>fit and well. “A bheil sibh gu spìdeil.”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112470008">
            <form>
               <orth>coidhligeadh</orth>
            </form>
            <def>applied to someone who is engaged in demanding inconvenient labour. I think this word also contains a sense of gathering. Heard this word whilst informant was busy gathering towels throughout the house, which were to be washed – “Tha mise a’ coidhligeadh an seo.”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AOHenley_KnockintorranFMacDonaldmisc-idp112512128">
            <form>
               <orth>coinnethal</orth>
            </form>
            <def>a sort of woolen scarf or cravat worn in days gone.</def>
         </entry>
